ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the above mentioned results, we constructed a simple energy level model to illustrate CDs' UC mechanism, (Figs. 2 and 3

                     ). At excitation energy >3.24 eV, possible transfer of electrons from valance band to the conduction band, and their subsequent recombination produces the standard PL emission. At excitation energy slightly less than the bandgap (2.8 eV-3.24 eV), electrons in deep emissive trap states (DETS) are excited and transfer to the surface emissive trap state (SETS) [17–19]. However, the generated holes in the DETS are unstable and quickly transfer to the valance band. Subsequent recombination of electrons in SETS produces the observed UCPL emission. Gradually decreasing UCPL intensity, (Fig. 2
                     , S4, and S5), is caused by decreased emissive trap state density. With further excitation energy reduction (2.33 eV-2.8 eV), only shallow emissive trap states (ShETS) can be excited [17–19]. Some incident photons are absorbed by these ShETS, producing single-photon upconversion PL emission. However, low density of ShETS could inhibit the absorbtion of all available photons. The remaining photons are possibly absorbed by electrons in the valance band and transferred to the conduction band by a two-photon process. Therefore, when CDs were excited by lower energy photons, fewer photons were absorbed by emissive trap states, and the valance band absorbed more photons. As excitation wavelength is increased, the two-photon process gradually dominated the UC process.
